Chapter 1: Introduction
The manufacturing industry is rapidly adopting intelligent technologies such as Artificial Intelligence (AI), Internet of Things (IoT), cloud computing, and advanced communication systems to improve operational efficiency. These technologies form the foundation of Industry 4.0, enabling continuous monitoring and optimization of industrial equipment.
In modern manufacturing environments, machines continuously generate operational data, including temperature, vibration, power consumption, production speed, and communication metrics. Analyzing this sensor data provides valuable insights into machine health and allows organizations to identify abnormal operating conditions before equipment failures occur.
Traditional maintenance strategies generally fall into two categories:
•	Reactive Maintenance, where repairs are performed after a machine has failed. 
•	Preventive Maintenance, where maintenance is scheduled at regular intervals regardless of machine condition. 
Both approaches have limitations. Reactive maintenance often results in unexpected downtime and costly repairs, while preventive maintenance can lead to unnecessary servicing and increased operational expenses.
Predictive maintenance addresses these challenges by using machine learning techniques to analyze sensor data and detect early signs of machine degradation. Instead of relying on fixed maintenance schedules, predictive maintenance continuously evaluates equipment health and recommends maintenance only when necessary.
In this project, the Isolation Forest algorithm was employed to identify anomalous machine behavior using historical manufacturing data. Feature engineering techniques were applied to improve anomaly detection by capturing temporal patterns and deviations in machine performance. An interactive Streamlit dashboard was developed to present machine health indicators, maintenance risk levels, historical trends, and production insights in an easy-to-understand format.
The proposed system demonstrates how predictive analytics can improve maintenance planning, reduce downtime, optimize resource utilization, and support intelligent decision-making in 6G-enabled smart manufacturing environments.
