Chapter 4: Literature Review
Predictive maintenance has become one of the most important applications of Artificial Intelligence within Industry 4.0. Researchers have proposed several machine learning techniques to identify abnormal machine behavior using industrial sensor data.
One of the most widely used unsupervised anomaly detection algorithms is Isolation Forest, introduced by Liu, Ting, and Zhou (2008). Unlike traditional classification methods, Isolation Forest does not require labeled failure data. Instead, it isolates observations by constructing random decision trees and identifies anomalies based on the number of splits required to separate each observation. This makes it particularly suitable for industrial environments where machine failures are relatively rare.
Recent research has demonstrated that feature engineering significantly improves predictive maintenance performance. Rolling averages, sensor deviation metrics, vibration-to-power ratios, and temporal error trends provide additional information beyond raw sensor readings and enable more accurate identification of abnormal operating conditions.
Visualization also plays an important role in predictive maintenance. Interactive dashboards developed using modern visualization frameworks such as Streamlit and Plotly allow maintenance engineers to monitor machine health, investigate anomalies, and make informed maintenance decisions without requiring extensive technical expertise.
The proposed system combines feature engineering, Isolation Forest anomaly detection, and interactive dashboard visualization to provide a comprehensive predictive maintenance solution for smart manufacturing.







