Chapter 10: Isolation Forest Algorithm
Overview
Isolation Forest is an unsupervised anomaly detection algorithm introduced by Liu, Ting, and Zhou (2008). Unlike traditional classification algorithms, Isolation Forest does not require labeled training data.
The algorithm isolates observations by recursively selecting random features and random split values. Anomalies require fewer splits to isolate because they differ significantly from normal observations.
________________________________________
Working Principle
The Isolation Forest algorithm follows these steps:
1.	Randomly select a feature. 
2.	Randomly choose a split value. 
3.	Divide the data into partitions. 
4.	Continue partitioning until each observation is isolated. 
5.	Calculate the average path length. 
6.	Assign an anomaly score. 
Observations with shorter path lengths are more likely to be anomalies.
________________________________________
Why Isolation Forest?
Isolation Forest was selected because it offers several advantages for predictive maintenance:
•	Does not require labeled failure data. 
•	Handles large datasets efficiently. 
•	Performs well with high-dimensional sensor data. 
•	Detects rare machine anomalies effectively. 
•	Computationally efficient for real-time applications. 
________________________________________

Model Parameters
The Isolation Forest model was configured using the following parameters:
Parameter	Value
Number of Trees (n_estimators)	200
Contamination	0.05
Random State	42
The contamination parameter assumes that approximately 5% of observations represent anomalous machine behavior.
