Chapter 19: Future Scope
The proposed predictive maintenance system demonstrates the successful application of machine learning for detecting abnormal machine behavior in smart manufacturing environments. Although the current implementation provides accurate anomaly detection and interactive visualization, several improvements can be incorporated in future versions to enhance its capabilities.
19.1 Deep Learning-Based Anomaly Detection
Future work may include the implementation of deep learning techniques such as Autoencoders and Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks. These models can learn complex nonlinear relationships within sensor data and improve anomaly detection accuracy.
19.2 Remaining Useful Life (RUL) Prediction
The current system identifies abnormal machine behavior but does not estimate how long a machine can continue operating before failure. Incorporating Remaining Useful Life prediction models would enable maintenance teams to schedule repairs more effectively.
19.3 Real-Time IoT Integration
The present project uses historical manufacturing data. Future systems can connect directly to IoT sensors and industrial communication protocols to perform continuous monitoring and real-time anomaly detection.
19.4 Cloud Deployment
Deploying the application on cloud platforms such as AWS, Microsoft Azure, or Google Cloud would enable remote monitoring of manufacturing plants from any location.
19.5 Automated Maintenance Alerts
Email notifications, SMS alerts, or mobile application notifications can be integrated into the system to automatically inform maintenance engineers whenever a machine enters the High-Risk category.
19.6 Explainable Artificial Intelligence (XAI)
Future versions can incorporate Explainable AI techniques such as SHAP or LIME to explain why a machine has been classified as anomalous. This increases transparency and improves user trust in machine learning predictions.
19.7 Digital Twin Integration
The predictive maintenance system can be integrated with digital twin technology, allowing virtual representations of physical machines to simulate machine behavior and optimize maintenance schedules.
